Data Types in C Sharp ....

What is a Bit?
A bit is the smallest unit of data.
A bit can store only
0 or 1 That's it. Nothing else.
Think of it like a light switch.
OFF = 0 , ON = 1
Note : 8 bits make - 1 Byte . Suppose we have : 10110010, 
Count them - 1 0 1 1 0 0 1 0 , 8 bits = 1 byte .

One Bit means only 1 value either 0 or 1 not 01 or 10 thease are two bits not one 
Suppose you have just one box. [ ] It can store only 0 or 1
Never 01 because 01 needs two places. Two Bits Now suppose you have two boxes.
[ ] [ ] Each box can independently store 0 or 1 Let's see every possibility.
00, First box = 0, Second box = 0 
01, First box = 0, Second box = 1
10, First box = 1, Second box = 0
11, First box = 1, Second box = 1
Notice something.
Each individual box still stores only one value: 0 or 1
But when we put two bits together, they create four different combinations.
Three Bits 
Now imagine three boxes. [ ] [ ] [ ]
Each box again stores only 0 or 1
Possible combinations become
000
001
010
011
100
101
110
111
Total = 8 combinations.

So, if n bits are there then total number of combination would be : 2^n

1- INTEGERAL Data type 
It can be dived into two categories. 
(i) Signed Integers : means it can store only positive values.
(ii) Unsigned Integers : means it can store both positive and negative values 

Data Type   	Bytes	    Bits	    Signed?	    Range
sbyte	        1	        8	        Yes	        -128 to 127
byte	        1	        8	        No	        0 to 255
short	        2	        16	        Yes	        -32,768 to 32,767
ushort	        2	        16	        No	        0 to 65,535
int	            4	        32	        Yes	        -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647
uint	        4	        32	        No	        0 to 4,294,967,295
long	        8	        64	        Yes	        Very large positive and negative values
ulong	        8	        64	        No	        Even larger positive values only

So if int is taking 4 bytes space in memory it means it can store 8x4 = 32 bit in memory so the total possible 
combination would be 2^32 4,294,967,296 possible values if it is unsigned called uint.
Example : uint number = 25;
The computer stores it as 00000000 00000000 00000000 00011001.
and because the counting tarts from zero we do 2^32-1 and because 1 bit is use for sign in case of signed data type 
we do 2^31 for positive numbers the count starts from zero and for negative numbers the count starts from -1 .
That's why the range for int is -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647 not ..........48 .
Data Types the complete picture ...
│
├── Integral Types (Whole Numbers)
│   │
│   ├── Signed
│   │   ├── sbyte (8 bits)
│   │   ├── short (16 bits)
│   │   ├── int (32 bits)
│   │   └── long (64 bits)
│   │
│   └── Unsigned
│       ├── byte (8 bits)
│       ├── ushort (16 bits)
│       ├── uint (32 bits)
│       └── ulong (64 bits)
│
├── Floating Point Types
│   ├── float
│   ├── double
│   └── decimal
│
├── Character
│   └── char
│
├── Boolean
│   └── bool
│
└── Text
    └── string

===========================================================================================================
The **`float`** data type in C# is a **32-bit (4-byte)** floating-point type used to store numbers with decimal values.
It provides approximately **7 significant digits of precision**, meaning the first 7 meaningful digits of a number 
are stored accurately, regardless of the position of the decimal point. Because `float` follows the IEEE 754 floating-point 
standard, some decimal values cannot be represented exactly, which may lead to small rounding errors. For higher precision,
C# provides the **`double`** data type, which is **64-bit (8-byte)** and offers approximately **15–16 significant 
digits of precision**, making it the default choice for most scientific and mathematical calculations.
The **`decimal`** data type is **128-bit (16-byte)** and provides **28–29 significant digits of precision**. 
It stores decimal values with much greater accuracy than `float` and `double`, making it the preferred choice 
for financial, banking, and monetary calculations where precision is critical.

Imagine you have a notebook that can only hold 7 digits.
You can write 1234567 perfectly. You can also write 1.234567 perfectly. 
You can also write 0.0001234567 perfectly.
Because in every case, the notebook only needs to remember 7 important digits.
It doesn't care where the decimal point is. Then what is the exponent doing? When you see 3.4 × 10^38
The computer actually stores two things:
The significant digits (called the mantissa or significand)
The position of the decimal point (stored as an exponent)
Just like scientific notation.
Example 123456789 can be written as 1.23456789 × 10^8
The computer stores 1.234567 (about 7 significant digits for float) and 10^8 separately.

This is why float can represent very large and very small numbers even though it only keeps about 7 significant 
digits accurate.

============================================================================================================
A string is a sequence (collection) of characters.
Example:
string name = "Piyush";
In c# to write a character we use single quotes and for string double quotes are used.
Is a string a primitive data type? No. 
Unlike
int
float
bool
char
string is actually a reference type (a class). That means it behaves differently in memory.
We'll learn that when we study stack vs heap memory.
For now, just remember:

string
│
├── Built from characters
├── Stores text
└── Reference type

Strings are immutable (Very Important)
Suppose:
string name = "Piyush";
Now you write:
name = "Rahul";
Does the computer change ..
Piyush into Rahul
No.
It creates a new string:

Before

name
 │
 ▼
"Piyush"

After

name
 │
 ▼
"Rahul"

"Piyush" still exists until the Garbage Collector removes it.

======================================================================================================
What is an Escape Sequence?
An escape sequence is a special character combination that begins with a backslash (\). It tells the compiler:
"Don't treat the next character as ordinary text. Give it a special meaning."

Verbatim String Literal....
Now imagine writing a Windows path like this: "C:\\Users\\Piyush\\Desktop\\Projects\\Portfolio"
Looks ugly, right? C# gives us Verbatim String Literals.
Syntax :  @"..."
The @ tells the compiler: "Treat everything inside as plain text."
Example :
string path = @"C:\Users\Piyush\Desktop\Projects";
Output
C:\Users\Piyush\Desktop\Projects

Multi-line Strings 
One of the biggest advantages of verbatim strings is writing multiple lines.
string text = @"Hello
Welcome
To C#";
Output :
Hello
Welcome
To C#
Without @, this would cause a compilation error.